Barack Obama will be the fourth US President to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
The diploma, medal and $1.4 million check will receive them, among other things, for the exceptional effort in strengthening global diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The White House chief and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and have a lot to do.
First, a visit to the Nobel Institute, where he will for the first time meet the five members of the committee that, in October, elected him from 172 people and 33 organizations.
Afterwards, the presidential couple is scheduled to meet with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth president to receive it, although the third to receive it in his office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the award, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid this issue, knowing that he is receiving the award as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts increased further with the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which does not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, the diploma and the check of ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million Czech crowns).
It is proposed to donate charitable parafines, but has not yet decided to which organization in particular.
During their full program, the President and his wife will attend a banquet, in addition to the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests.
Obama had a rather reserved attitude toward the award from the beginning.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling of not deserved it at all.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for all who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned it represents "a challenge to take action."
