U.S.: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan issue the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered the foolishest.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only does the same text use the phrase “like in Iraq” several times, but it also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush’s January 2007 statement for his own statement: “A New Way Forward.”
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from civil war, and that criticized him as “an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences.”
The following months, however, demonstrated that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that today there is nothing talking about Iraq in the news.
Bush’s reputation did not improve, yet objectively left his successor a much more favourable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to be repeated.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal, who, even despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected the indecisive gunmen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn’t think of anything better, so at least he deceived the general over 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of Obama’s entire strategy seems to be its goal, starting to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finishing this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will yield the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: it is not possible to trust anyone and no agreement is fulfilled.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, though formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin, after which patriarchal tribal relations will remain.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to the confusing relationships, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is “capable of action,” a minimum goal of the whole operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy collides with his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war for "coming home soon," will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date of the withdrawal of the troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will see it as an indirect declaration of the American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans have less and less willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their voters, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and increased sanctions have no effect on Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to seek the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left for the presidential election and that is why there is still a lot of time left to find another strategy, if it is a total failure.
