A Czech Discovery: An Effective Substance Even in the 'Colded' HIV Virus
Team of Czech and German scientists test new compounds capable of moderating HIV spread in the body
The main advantage of this enhanced substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some medicines already available.
AIDS can’t be cured until now.
However, patients’ lives may be significantly prolonged thanks to a mixture of drugs that prevent HIV virus replication in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, the so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the medications no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarborans have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metallocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way than all drugs used today, and that is why they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared to know the molecular mechanism of their bond to the albumin of the virus.
The metallocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are bonded by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A traitor and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the virus’ life cycle.
Without HIV protease, HIV virus fractionation does not occur and no mature and infectious corpuscles of the virus would be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
