Managing Revolution or End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to "values" determined from above as it was previously about imposing on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to strategies of conquest of the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to the factors of preference of customers is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization severely compromises the development of all intellectual functions of the company, especially of R&D and, even more, of business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) “demands that all parties involved ... have proactive behavior and a forward-looking vision”; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we call for a managerial revolution, which would consist in putting employees at the center of the concerns of the company as well as the customer.
Internal opinion surveys have relative usefulness.
Will internal opinion surveys, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many lapses, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the ancient behaviorist theory that the American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the “commands” (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management posture, inadapted to today’s world.
Identifying and measuring mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises, implies adopting a finalistic vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating into every reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, engagement with the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to make part of their dreams, ambitions and projects a reality.
Today, only studies from Motifuntional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to assess what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, business managers can monitor, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resource management "in place".
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
