The dinosaur's cradle
The Tawa hallae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1.50 meters tall that ran over the two strong rear legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of millions of years later, this would not have been something special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window toward the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, propagation and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes we have found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, this is something unprecedented for Triasic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they gathered in total the remains of five specimens.
A find confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional finding: "Triasian dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the sauries were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the sauropods quadruped known as the "long neck" and their relatives, and the Trinithisch species.
According to Nesbitt and his colleagues' analysis, Tawa hachae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt comments.
For example, in the skull of Tawa, researchers found signs of airbags, such as those that also possess the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to airbags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa findae, the bones of the spine were obviously partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag theropod, comments Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the later giant sauropods also possessed airbags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers deduced that sauries first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages were initially separated and spread from South America across all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single earth mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say the team found along with Tawa find the remains of two other theropods not very closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single relative predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three migratory waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study Science.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a brother group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, comments Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Their opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is barely anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare collateral line from reptiles to dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
While in the Triasic dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other sauries.
Towards the end of the Triassic dinosaurs spread all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship extinct at the limit of the Triassic to the Jurassic.
Successful stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, Martin Sander comments.
It could have been a massive extinction that dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to defeat opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact halts the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triasic and since then had a miserable existence: the mammals.
