Oniric worlds
In a vigilant state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of mentally ill people and drug addicts, the boundaries between imagination and reality are fading away.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can surrender without barriers to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, anyone who experiences sleep-like states during waking up, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is considered most of the time in the modern Western world as crazy or drug addict, or at least as a maniac.
But such images and voices arise not only in the mentally ill or the drugged.
The fault is our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings, or write novels, sometimes make the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality uncovered.
Onirically modified alert states of consciousness may appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although triggers and effects can be distinguished, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, the states of shamanic possession, and psychoses and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain – especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been disrupted and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During a schizophrenic psychosis very often complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts appear.
Gravity no longer has power over it.
The relationship between madness and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of sleep in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness with the oniric states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the unintended and unlocalized forms".
It is the autumn of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book figure.
Its body is two-dimensional and scandalously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over it, it's floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with red muzzles like blood, deformed, scratching their teeth.
They are chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, thrown him against the walls, he feels the pains throughout the body.
Striking and evil voices resonate from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer bear them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. pulls out two cables from the stereo, ties them together to form a hanging knot, and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
It climbs into a horn and puts the knot around the neck.
Jump. Jump.
The rope is loosened.
“What a lesson for you!” shout the voices in a choir that breaks his tympanes, “Go to the clinic and have them heal you!”
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
The cause that caused it was LSD.
Its diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, in addition it is maniac-depressive, takes medications, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the lifetime of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside and the inner world, and fall into a state of overexcitation that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of greatness, relationship disorders, or persecutionary mania.
Especially widespread is hearing voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain is no longer able to filter the disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the gates to a stream of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, says professor Thomas Fuchs, chief doctor of the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed to it.
At the same time he enters a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
This is why schizophrenic people often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general, it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in life
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality perceived in psychosis remain in principle as it is."
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, distancement from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers, it is still unknown why our brain makes cabrioles.
According to Fuchs, states of exception can lead anyone to lose contact with reality on a temporary basis.
But not all people develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes there are also other determinants.
The researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains an unknown how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when a pre-disposition already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the transmitting system of the brain.
When the brain warms up
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer from their hallucinations and take very expensive medications to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experiment with some, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been compiling reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf, published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
These include, along with psychic disorders such as boundary personality disorder or depressions, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer’s and cranial brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, the brain of healthy people also suffers from hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memories that are normally repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are hyperactive or poorly cohibited; when our brain gets warm, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this state in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, sickness of love or other brain states of exception.
In recent studies, up to one-third of respondents reported having experienced hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, lived in a small town in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and went to a high school.
A regular girl.
