Madness is also a work of art by despair.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers from a stimulus restriction, it is highly likely that after a while he will begin to have hallucinations.
I think the brain is unemployed and is responsible for finding entertainment.
Sarah K., the only daughter, was little afraid of the other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at age 13, he learned that the man he calls dad since he has been using reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, those affected like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. "Every experience," Kasten says, "has place in the brain, reality projects there.
