75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women from younger generations who want to become mothers.
This is revealed by the study ‘Fecundity and Trajectory of Women in Spain’, prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of couple coexistence and the number of children, depending on whether or not they work and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job, start coexistence before, advance first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and maternity, and have fewer offspring.
Women aged 35 to 49 with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting coexistence, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their vital career to achieve them, which has led them to postpone union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a great deal of influence on maternity but less on the timing of pairing,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that distinguishes the age of women when they marry and when they have the first stem.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which they marry and the age at which they have the first child.
The difference also remains among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, women with elementary and higher studies were first mothers at average 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
Another division among women is also established based on their level of education.
While those who have elementary studies marry and have their first child before getting a stable job, those of middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child.
