Emergency braking aid is already mandatory
As with the anti-blocking of ABS brakes and will pass with the ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a lack period is set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, because of their way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions per range.
The emergency braking assistant is to increase the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency, which the system detects by the tramp that the driver gives.
But it doesn’t always keep that pressure up to the end.
According to a study conducted by the car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not reached the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, demands the maximum from the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 deadly accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented a year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided - when so-called smart emergency braking systems become popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps you increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort to the brakes to minimize damage.
